INTRODUCTION :

The purpose of this project is to analyse the data related to covid-19 cases as well as deaths, collected at the country level (United States) and The global level and produce a reproducible report in R.

The questions of interest are :

  • Analyzing and Plotting the covid -19 cases and deaths till date for the entire US nation.
  • Analyzing and Plotting the covid -19 cases and deaths till date for a particular state of interest (New York)
  • Analysing and Plotting the daily new cases/deaths curve for the entire US nation
  • Analysing and Plotting the daily new cases/deaths curve for a particular state of interest (New York)
  • List of top 10 worst performing US states having highest death rates ( deaths per thousand population)
  • List of top 10 best performing US states having lowest death rates ( deaths per thousand population)
  • Creating a linear Model to predict probable death rates(deaths/thousand people) for perspective case rates(cases/thousand people)

Data Source :

The source of our data is [Johns Hopkins University]https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 github sites.

This is the data repository for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus Visual Dashboard operated by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CSSE). Also, Supported by ESRI Living Atlas Team and the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Lab (JHU APL).

The data contains multiple .csv files containing daily covid-19 cases and deaths for various nations of the world as well as the detailed (county level) data for United States of America.

url_in <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_"
file_names <- c("confirmed_global.csv",
                "deaths_global.csv",
                "confirmed_US.csv",
                "deaths_US.csv")
urls <- str_c(url_in,file_names) 

global_cases <- read_csv(urls[1], show_col_types = FALSE)
global_deaths <- read_csv(urls[2], show_col_types = FALSE)

Updating the global dataset to include population data

The global dataset does not contain any population data. Hence, to do comparitive analysis among different countries, we are adding population data to it. Also we are making a new column combined key to represent holistic location identity.

global <- global %>%
  unite("Combined_Key",
        c(Province_State, Country_Region),
        sep = ", ",
        na.rm = TRUE,
        remove = FALSE)

** Data Visualization and Analysis**

Considering the US data set and analysing it for each state.

Making a US_by_state dataset to have state-wise statistics of covid cases and deaths till date.
#Clubbing all the county data(Admin2) to their respective states

US_by_state <- US %>%
  group_by(Province_State, Country_Region, date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases), deaths = sum(deaths),
            Population = sum(Population)) %>%
  mutate(deaths_per_mill = deaths *1000000 / Population) %>%
  select(Province_State, Country_Region, date,
         cases, deaths, deaths_per_mill, Population) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Province_State', 'Country_Region'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
Making a US_totals dataset to have a complete picture of USs covid cases and deaths at the Nation Level till date.
# Clubbing all the US states data to the Federal(US) level.

US_totals <- US_by_state %>%
  group_by(Country_Region, date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases), deaths = sum(deaths),
            Population = sum(Population)) %>%
  mutate(deaths_per_mill = deaths *1000000 / Population) %>%
  select(Country_Region, date,
         cases, deaths, deaths_per_mill, Population) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Country_Region'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
print(US_totals)

Plotting the total USs cases and deaths till date.

US_totals %>%
  filter(cases > 0) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = cases)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = "cases")) +
  geom_point(aes(color = "cases")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = deaths, color = "deaths")) +
  geom_point(aes(y = deaths, color = "deaths")) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "COVID19 in United States", y= NULL)

Analysis of the US total cases and deaths Plot :

The above plot of Total covid-19 cases and deaths till date in United States clearly shows that the increase in covid deaths/cases was higher in the starting phase of pandemic and then the graphs have started becoming less steeper with time. The reason behind the same may be a better understanding of the disease, greater preparedness to fight covid with time along with aggressive vaccination drive.

Also , the curves for cases and deaths show a parallel shape with a slight lag in time, clearly suggesting that their is a positive correlation between cases and deaths. Also , the lag justifies the argument that cases today can be a casuality of tomorrow.

Analyze the data

Calculating the new cases and deaths being added daily for the entire country as well as for each state. Using the lag function to do the same.

US_by_state <- US_by_state %>%
  mutate(new_cases = cases - lag(cases),
         new_deaths = deaths - lag(deaths))
US_totals <- US_totals %>%
  mutate(new_cases = cases - lag(cases),
         new_deaths = deaths - lag(deaths))

Plotting the new cases and deaths on graph

#### Analysis of the COVID 19 in US-new cases, new deaths curve

As can be seen from the graph, the new cases and new deaths are showing parallel curves. Also, both new cases and new deaths have a roughly sinusoidal shape suggesting multiple waves of covid-19 in the nation. The new cases keep rising till a peak and then decrease, representing the first wave of covid, followed by similar increase- peak-decrease phase of second wave. The multiple waves can be a result of new variants, carelessness of people due to pandemic fatigue etc.

The curve of New york new cases and new deaths are on expectation lines of the data for nation as a whole. But the variation in the new deaths is much more in New York. Best Performing States Vs Worst Performing States

we will now be comparing how different US states performed, by first calculating the cases per thousand population, deaths per thousand population and then applying the slice_max and slice_min functions. This will give us the best performing and worst performing states of US.

Best performing 10 states
US_state_totals <- US_by_state %>% 
  group_by(Province_State) %>%
  summarize(deaths = max(deaths), cases = max(cases),
            population = max(Population), 
            cases_per_thou = 1000* cases / population,
            deaths_per_thou = 1000 * deaths / population) %>% 
  filter(cases > 0, population > 0) 
US_state_totals %>%
  slice_min(deaths_per_thou, n = 10)

Modeling the data

We will be creating a linear model using the lm() function which can predict the value of dependent variable(here deaths per thousand) for any potential value of independent variable ( here cases per thousand). Thereafter, we will plot it using ggplot.

mod <- lm(deaths_per_thou ~ cases_per_thou, data = US_state_totals)
summary(mod)

Conclusion

The Covid-19 analysis leads us to the conclusion that the pandemic started in USA with a very high rate initially, but then slowly decreased in rate. This may be due to localised herd immunity and better administrative response to deal with the pandemic.These findings have been inferred by plotting the total cases and deaths for the nation. Similar plot drawn for the state of New York supports these findings. Also the curves of new daily cases and deaths being added also suppliment the same findings as true.

Also, the analysis of the global Covid data leads us to the conclusion that countries with higher population, elder demography, and inadequate health infrastructure are at the top of chart in terms of cases and casualities by covid. For Ex. Brazil and India are both very populous nation with a very weak health system and both occupy top 3 positions in terms of covid cases and casuality.

Also, It is a little surprising that how a developed nation like US, with one of the finest health systems, has the highest number of cases and casuality due to covid till date. One possible explanation for this can be due to more accurate reporting system adopted by US as compared to other nations.

Possible Sources of Bias

The possible sources of bias can be at various levels:

Collection of data level : * due to inadequate/non-representative sample being surveyed. * due to false positive/negative covid- 19 test reports * due to different reporting systems adopted by different states. For ex. some states may be disregarding deaths due to heart-attack post covid recovery as covid deaths * due to human error in reporting the responses of survey

Analysis of Data level : * Analysis after data visualization can bring in personal bias in some form. * Any bias in the data can be propogated to become bigger through the modeling.
